tweet: I think there's always room for kindness in teaching. Be the kind teacher (while still being fair, upholding your syllabus, etc...) But there's far more room to be kind in academia than most people think is possible.

name: Woodzick
description: They/Them. Writer, Actor, Director, Producer, Marketer, Editor. Host of @TheatricalM, distributed by @AmericanTheatre. #ActuallyAutistic #BlackLivesMatter
tweet: Before my students took a test, I would tell offer, "I want you to take a deep breath. Please remember that the grade you get on this test has no reflection of your worth as a human being."

name: Woodzick
description: They/Them. Writer, Actor, Director, Producer, Marketer, Editor. Host of @TheatricalM, distributed by @AmericanTheatre. #ActuallyAutistic #BlackLivesMatter
tweet:
Take away #2: 

Let students submit questions for assessments. (I gave them extra credit for doing so.) 

Nothing prepared me better for writing tests than reviewing the questions my students thought should be included.

name: Woodzick
description: They/Them. Writer, Actor, Director, Producer, Marketer, Editor. Host of @TheatricalM, distributed by @AmericanTheatre. #ActuallyAutistic #BlackLivesMatter
tweet:
The assignment was built in the online learning platform and students could type their essays or write them by hand, take a photo and upload it to the platform. 

(You could take it a step further and allow audio essays as well.)

name: Woodzick
description: They/Them. Writer, Actor, Director, Producer, Marketer, Editor. Host of @TheatricalM, distributed by @AmericanTheatre. #ActuallyAutistic #BlackLivesMatter
tweet:
In my lecture class, my students wrote one-minute essays once a week. 

These were subjective questions that gave me weekly insights into how my students were responding to the material and my teaching style. 

It also provided a way for students to participate without speaking.

name: Woodzick
description: They/Them. Writer, Actor, Director, Producer, Marketer, Editor. Host of @TheatricalM, distributed by @AmericanTheatre. #ActuallyAutistic #BlackLivesMatter
tweet:
She realized that she could help more students by educating and supporting instructors than she could by teaching 2-4 classes a semester. 

She gave me two incredible takeaways: 

1) Offer one-minute essays as in-class assignments.
https://t.co/TVKCPBpkNe

name: Woodzick
description: They/Them. Writer, Actor, Director, Producer, Marketer, Editor. Host of @TheatricalM, distributed by @AmericanTheatre. #ActuallyAutistic #BlackLivesMatter
tweet:
I got to TA for one semester & then I was handed a syllabus. That was my training for teaching. If your institution has an office that supports teachers, make an appointment. 

I met with an amazing educator who had gained tenure and then quit, specifically to work with teachers.

name: Woodzick
description: They/Them. Writer, Actor, Director, Producer, Marketer, Editor. Host of @TheatricalM, distributed by @AmericanTheatre. #ActuallyAutistic #BlackLivesMatter
tweet:
2) This lets YOU know if your assumptions about who is taking your class and why are correct. 

Did they love the subject?
Did they want to take the class with a friend?
Did they hear the class was fun or easy?
Did the schedule allow them to keep their part-time job? 
All valid!

name: Woodzick
description: They/Them. Writer, Actor, Director, Producer, Marketer, Editor. Host of @TheatricalM, distributed by @AmericanTheatre. #ActuallyAutistic #BlackLivesMatter
tweet:
Ask them why they took your class. Assure them that you really want to know the reason. 

1) This lets them know that you actually value their opinion. Their worth in your class is not solely based on their capacity or ability to give you right or wrong answers.

name: Woodzick
description: They/Them. Writer, Actor, Director, Producer, Marketer, Editor. Host of @TheatricalM, distributed by @AmericanTheatre. #ActuallyAutistic #BlackLivesMatter
tweet: Ask for pronouns. Make it a short answer question instead of a multiple-choice question. Again, let them indicate if you need to hold an awareness of using their pronouns in front of the class.

name: Woodzick
description: They/Them. Writer, Actor, Director, Producer, Marketer, Editor. Host of @TheatricalM, distributed by @AmericanTheatre. #ActuallyAutistic #BlackLivesMatter
tweet: Create a pathway for students to introduce themselves to you one on one. Make it a quiz that is worth as many points as any other quiz you give. As them if they go by a name that's different than the roster AND if it's ok to call them by that name in front of the class.

name: Woodzick
description: They/Them. Writer, Actor, Director, Producer, Marketer, Editor. Host of @TheatricalM, distributed by @AmericanTheatre. #ActuallyAutistic #BlackLivesMatter
tweet: I'm non-binary and use they/them pronouns. I added those to my syllabus, email signature and when I wrote my name on the whiteboard for the first time. You never know which one of your students needs to see this (for a variety of reasons.)

name: Woodzick
description: They/Them. Writer, Actor, Director, Producer, Marketer, Editor. Host of @TheatricalM, distributed by @AmericanTheatre. #ActuallyAutistic #BlackLivesMatter
tweet:
I haven't taught undergraduate classes for about a year. 

(I hope I will again!) 

Inspired by a conversation I had on Twitter tonight with a fellow educator, I am sharing some of my teaching tips. 

If you're a #teacher, I hope you find them helpful! 

Thread:

name: Woodzick
description: They/Them. Writer, Actor, Director, Producer, Marketer, Editor. Host of @TheatricalM, distributed by @AmericanTheatre. #ActuallyAutistic #BlackLivesMatter

name: Woodzick
description: They/Them. Writer, Actor, Director, Producer, Marketer, Editor. Host of @TheatricalM, distributed by @AmericanTheatre. #ActuallyAutistic #BlackLivesMatter
tweet:
@GaetaAmy I learned SO much from the one-minute essays--a great starter question is "Why did you take this class? No, really--I want to know!" 

Having a pathway for student feedback throughout the semester was so lovely and let me know if I was being clear in what I was teaching.

name: Woodzick
description: They/Them. Writer, Actor, Director, Producer, Marketer, Editor. Host of @TheatricalM, distributed by @AmericanTheatre. #ActuallyAutistic #BlackLivesMatter
tweet: @GaetaAmy Literally giving them credit to write about what they actually thought about the content in class that week. They shared studies about how that helped to engage students more overall and evened the playing field for those who didn't want to speak up in front of their peers...

name: Woodzick
description: They/Them. Writer, Actor, Director, Producer, Marketer, Editor. Host of @TheatricalM, distributed by @AmericanTheatre. #ActuallyAutistic #BlackLivesMatter
tweet: @GaetaAmy :-) Just to nerd out a bit more--I once talked with someone who had gotten tenure and quit work in the educator support center because they knew they could help student more in that role (!) They suggested using one-minute essays each week: basically, no wrong answers...

name: Woodzick
description: They/Them. Writer, Actor, Director, Producer, Marketer, Editor. Host of @TheatricalM, distributed by @AmericanTheatre. #ActuallyAutistic #BlackLivesMatter
tweet:
@GaetaAmy I also liked to say this before assessments: "Please keep in mind that this test is absolutely no indication of your worth as a human being." I got positive feedback about those words helping students with their test anxiety. 

Thanks for letting me ramble--I miss teaching!

name: Woodzick
description: They/Them. Writer, Actor, Director, Producer, Marketer, Editor. Host of @TheatricalM, distributed by @AmericanTheatre. #ActuallyAutistic #BlackLivesMatter
tweet: @GaetaAmy It always made me happy to see what students sent in and gave me insight into who they were as humans. And it was kind of a good indicator at how many reminder emails I might need to send out as assignment reminders, etc...

name: Woodzick
description: They/Them. Writer, Actor, Director, Producer, Marketer, Editor. Host of @TheatricalM, distributed by @AmericanTheatre. #ActuallyAutistic #BlackLivesMatter
tweet: @GaetaAmy For sure! Good luck!  If you don't have plans to read the entire syllabus out loud during an early class, I always liked sneaking extra credit "Easter Eggs" in to reward folx who read all the way through. Email a pet photo, favorite parody video, etc...breaks the ice! :-)

name: Woodzick
description: They/Them. Writer, Actor, Director, Producer, Marketer, Editor. Host of @TheatricalM, distributed by @AmericanTheatre. #ActuallyAutistic #BlackLivesMatter
tweet: @GaetaAmy It would depend on the energy I got from the instructor--if they seemed like they actually meant these statements or were throwing them on their syllabus as an empty gesture.

Try different postures (sitting, laying down, walking) and see what works for you. 

Break it down into simple pieces: focus either on your breath OR noticing your thoughts.

When you misgender an actor in the rehearsal room, it has the potential of them dissociating in order to protect themselves. 

This robs them of the gift of being completely present in the room, which is what is required of actors.

tweet:
Customer (on phone): She she she she she
Me (overly chipper):  Actually, it's they, thank you so much.
Customer: Thanks for correcting me, but I don't get it.
Me (bursting into flames): Well, shucks, lemme explain it to you politely even though I shouldn't have to. 

AND SCENE.
